Diamondback Firearms is proud to present the DB9, a micro-compact 9mm pistol made entirely in the USA. Designed with safety in mind, the DB9 features a "ZERO-Energy" striker firing system with a mechanical firing pin block, a steel magazine catch to secure a sheet metal magazine and real windage-adjustable sights, all in a lightweight pistol. title: For Sale/Trade:  3 sets of body armor.  Trades prefered
postcontent:
Military type Body Armor.

 One PASGT (Personnel Armor System for Ground Troops) Vest. Medium in very good lightly used shape with the data card in the back it comes with the Chocolate chip and 3 color desert and covers. 50.00  

 One Canadian Military PASGT equivalent, it is medium and looks to be in new condition from the looks of it. 50.00 

 One Improved Outer Tactical Vest with hard armor E-SAPI plates. 700.00 Or Best Reasonable Offer or trade.

 The list of components:

 Soft armor panel inserts
 Four ballistic plate inserts (front and back plates and two side plates)
 Collar
 Deltoid and Auxiliary protector system (DAPs)
 The groin protector is not included

 This is a small vest with the expansion system built in it fits my 210 pound frame easily. 
 A key design feature for the IOTV is that the entire armor system is able to be released with the pull of a hidden lanyard. The armor then falls apart into its component pieces, providing a means for escape in case the wearer falls into water or becomes trapped in a hazardous environment.[5] The hidden release lanyard also allows medical personnel easier access to a casualty, which was one concern that was not addressed with the old Interceptor armor.

 The IOTV takes the weight of the vest off the shoulders and move it to the lower torso. It has a mesh inner cover that is designed to improve airflow inside of the armor. A back pad in the lower back area of the vest is designed to defeat fragmentation impacts to the lower back/kidney areas. The back pad does not provide ballistic protection. The vest can withstand a direct impact from a 7.62 millimeter (both NATO and ex-Soviet types) on the front or rear plates E-SAPI plates will provide protection to armor-piercing rounds (NIJ standard IV). The IOTV provides, without the ballistic ceramic plates inserted, protection from small caliber rounds (i.e. 9mm) and fragmentation. The soft kevlar panels have been tested to stop 9 mm 124 grain full metal jacket bullets at 1,400 ft/s (426 m/s) with minimal deformation and has a V-50 of roughly 1,525 ft/s (465 m/s). This means that the bullet has to be traveling faster than 1,525 ft/s for it to have more than a 50% chance of breaking through the soft armor panel. These specifications are similar to the NIJ standard level III-A certification, however, military standards do not require their vests to be NIJ certified. This is a huge improvement over the PASGT vest, and the Vietnam era fragmentation vest (which was made of nylon). Both only offered protection against fragmentation.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger ATI 10/22 .22 LR
postcontent:
So i purchased this brand new Ruger ATI 10/22 .22 Long Rifle, and realized for what I'm looking to do, I need something much more basic, so am interested in either trading or selling this particular 10/22 for one of your firearms or just selling outright.  This rifle is brand new, still in the box, and is the Ruger 10/22 ATI version.  None of the components on this have been used at all, everything is brand new including the Bushnell 3-9x40 scope, sling, bi-pod, etc.  

This is the cadillac version of the 10/22 with the stainless steel threaded barrel, factory flash suppressor, 6-position collapsible stock, etc.  It's pretty decked out but just not for me, I'm more interested in a 10/22 with a bull barrel, action job and Hogue stock, etc.  I have enough AR's as it is and want a break from the tactical look cause I don't get in gunfights too often here in downtown Portland.  Side note - I also have the premium factory Ruger scope rings for this rifle, those alone will run you about $80 or so.  

So, let me know if you're interested.  Hindsight is always 20/20, of course, but if I could take back my purchase I would have just bought a bone stock 10/22 and invested the extra money in the barrel and stock that I want, already have a brand new Leupold VX II to mount on it, just seems stupid to let all this go to waste if I'm just going to replace all the furniture.  This is a very nice rifle, don't get me wrong, just going for a different look so I don't get laughed at this hunting season when we're out plinking in downtime.

Thanks!

CW

title: For Sale:  Antique Nydar Model 47 Shotgun Sight
postcontent:
Nydar Model 47 shotgun sight, manufactured by the Swain Nelson Company in Glenview, Illinois. It is complete, in the original box, with instructions and leather lens cover. The sight is activated by ambient light; you get a large outer ring and inner dot that is projected onto the front lens. Even on a heavy overcast day, this sight works perfectly! 

The operating principle for this sight was taken directly from World War ll. Allied aircraft had similar sights that worked in the same way and were used with great success, with the reticle at the focus of a collimating lens that produces a virtual image of the reticle. The image is reflected off of an angled beam splitter so that the user (looking through the beam splitter will see the image at the focus of the collimating optics superimposed in the sight's field of view in focus at ranges up to infinity with near zero parallax. The inner dot represents 12 inches at 50 yards, while the outer ring is positioned so that the ring itself is always 24 inches from the inner dot. 

Asking $50 shipped OBO.

postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=57

The .454 Casull is one cartridge that Buffalo Bore Ammunition does not load to it's full pressure limit. When loaded to it's full pressure potential the .454 Casull can become unreliable and unpleasant to shoot. At upper pressure levels, heavy bullets tend to jump crimp - tying up the cylinder. (wouldn't this be great in an emergency) Also, fired brass can stick in the chambers. 

Buffalo Bore Ammunition feels that a 360 gr. bullet (or 325 gr. bullet at 1525 fps) at 1425 fps is still very powerful, comfortable to shoot, and TOTALLY RELIABLE. At these levels, these bullets give up nothing in killing performance.
